15–1365":"1315–1365","–Female":"Deceased","1240–1285":"1240–1285","1250–1326":"1250–1326","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1273":"1273","ABT 1238":"about 1238","1250":"1250","1291":"1291","1280":"1280","4 November 1285":"4 November 1285","24 de maio de 1326":"24 May 1326","1326":"1326","1315":"1315","1238":"1238","1336":"1336","abt 1315":"about 1315","1335":"1335","1268":"1268","       1343":"1343","1365":"1365","1343":"1343","1364":"1364","1328":"1328","Schweiz":"Switzerland","Tirol, Österreich":"Tirol, Austria","of,,Lienz,Austria":"Lienz, Tirol, Austria","Europa":"Europe","of Alpegg, Schwyz., Switz.":"Schwyz, Switzerland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Vatz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["East German: from a Germanized short form of the Slavic personal name <i>Ladislav</i> (see   Laca   and   Lacek  ).","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>laz</i> ‘ribbon, garment closure; fly (on pants)’."],"variants":[{"name":"Laca","meanings":["Basque: Castilianized form of <b>Laka</b>, from the vocabulary word <i>laka</i> ‘certain quantity of wheat paid for the mill’, applied as a topographic name or as a metonymic occupational name.","Slovak: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Ladislav</i> (see   Lacek  )."]},{"name":"Latzke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Heinz, Wilhelm.","German: from a pet form of   Latz   1."]}]},{"name":"Margareta","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Margarete","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margrethe","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretha","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]}]},{"name":"von","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Simplified spelling of   John   or a short form of   Jonathan .  The name is borne by the Canadian singer  Jon Vickers  (  b. 1926 ) and the American actor  Jon Voight  (  b. 1938 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jonathan","meanings":["Biblical name, meaning ‘God has given’, composed of the same elements as those of   Matthew  , but in reverse order. This is the name of several characters in the Bible, most notably a son of King Saul, who was a devoted friend and supporter of the young David, even when David and Saul were themselves at loggerheads (1 Samuel 31; 2 Samuel 1:19–26). The name is often taken as symbolic of steadfast friendship and loyalty. Well-known bearers of the name include the Irish clergyman and writer  Jonathan Swift  (  1667-1745 ), British theatre director  Jonathan Miller  (  b. 1934 ), British actor  Jonathan Pryce  (  b. 1947 ), and British television presenter  Jonathan Ross  (  b. 1960 )."]},{"name":"Jonn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jon   or  <b>John</b> ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1353604,"age":53,"year":"1291","julianDay":2192589,"description":"Three valleys in Central Switzerland unite against the counts of Habsburg and fight for autonomy. Cities join the confederacy. They conquer territories in northern and southern Switzerland.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1353605,"age":77,"year":"1315","julianDay":2201354,"description":"Decisive Battle against the counts of Habsburg.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Margareta von Vatz was born about 1238, in Lienz, Tirol, Austria, her father, Walter V. von Vaz, was 0 and her mother, Liutgard von Kirchberg, was -10. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Ulrich II von Matsch. She died in 1343, in Switzerland, at the age of 106."},"et":{"ABT 1238–       1343":"umbes 1238–1343","1238–1343":"1238–1343","1268–1335":"1268–1335","1275–1364":"1275–1364","1280–1336":"1280–1336","1273–1328":"1273–1328","1315–1365":"1315–1365","–Female":"Surnud","1240–1285":"1240–1285","1250–1326":"1250–1326","1275":"1275","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1273":"1273","ABT 1238":"umbes 1238","1250":"1250","1291":"1291","1280":"1280","4 November 1285":"4. november 1285","24 de maio de 1326":"24. mai 1326","1326":"1326","1315":"1315","1238":"1238","1336":"1336","abt 1315":"umbes 1315","1335":"1335","1268":"1268","       1343":"1343","1365":"1365","1343":"1343","1364":"1364","1328":"1328","Schweiz":"Šveits","Tirol, Österreich":"Tirol, Austria","of,,Lienz,Austria":"Lienz, Tirol, Austria","Europa":"Europe","of Alpegg, Schwyz., Switz.":"Schwyz, Šveits"},"fi":{"ABT 1238–       1343":"noin 1238–1343","1238–1343":"1238–1343","1268–1335":"1268–1335","1275–1364":"1275–1364","128